{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2f4b1076-8824-4652-9b03-e8f998f9888b","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or convert to Speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, use a **sidecar** or copy the tool binary in.\n- For a lower-level approach, you can use `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm CPU is spent in managed code.\n- If the container image is based on the **runtime-only** image (no SDK), install the tool globally via the standalone download instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"52fdbf48-35cf-4be4-bdda-bafb52122917","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes when experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":441,"requestId":"7811:8A8EB:1CE3245:202764F:69FA97FB"},"id":"40475a11-686a-4582-b65c-35f94f2436a6","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:23:17.469Z","parentId":"604a089c-f736-4bf4-a1e6-9d10b80ffe66"}
